column2:
Broadly speaking, the general public believes that Generative AI is an ecologically-devestating, job-stealing, utility-hoarding plagiarism engine.

In short, you'll need to convince the public that:
• You've adressesed the vast ecological damages AI data centers cause;
• That Canadian workers can feel safe and secure, knowing their jobs, it at least their income, is protected;
• That Canadians won't need to suffer skyrocketing utility bills, brown-outs, or water rationing as a result of a new AI data-center;
• and that companies will not profit from their creative property – both artistic and intellectual –being surreptitiously stolen, digested, and misinterpreted by an algorithm.

column4:
Given the significant impacts that the broad adoption of AI is likely to have on this generation of young workers, it is essential that both young people of working age and those still pursuing their education, be proactively and meaningfully engaged in designing and implementing initiatives that will aim to promote responsible AI use and trust in AI governance. Meaningful engagement of young people can be defined as intentional and sustained involvement of young people throughout a given policy process. In order to ensure young people are meaningfully engaged in policy processes surrounding AI, the below best practices should be followed: 
• Be prepared before engaging young people. This includes the leadership and staff ‘buying in’ to diverse, equitable and inclusive youth engagement, meaningful intergenerational collaboration and valuing young people’s unique abilities, and attitudes and stereotypes about young people being proactively addressed; 
• Establish adequate structures for youth engagement and allocate appropriate resources. This includes embedding youth engagement within the formal structures of the foundation as well as providing on-going financial and staff support; 
• Dedicate the time needed to establish relationships between adults and young people that center belonging, trust, and space for discomfort and ambiguity;
• Ensure young people are prepared for their involvement and supported throughout with thoughtful emotional support, a balance of safety and support as well as choice and challenge, just in time training, and ongoing mentorship; 
• Ensure young people are given the chance to make real decisions, take ownership over mission critical tasks and have a meaningful impact; 
• Ensure young people engage with the wider community through intergenerational collaboration and by embedding young people’s work within a wider network of support; and
• Regularly gather and share data about youth engagement efforts and regularly integrate feedback.

column2:
Le Canada doit s'allier avec les provinces canadiennes pour mettre en place:
- Un cadre strict pour interdire l'usage de l'IA à des fins de désinformation (fake news, hypertrucages);
- Des exigences légales en matière d'optimisation énergétique pour les fournisseurs d'IA;
- Des protections proactives des données personnelles et sensibles, notamment par une transparence accrue en termes d'usage des données et par leur stockage sur des serveurs sécurisés en sol canadien;
- Des programmes de sensibilisation accessibles et gratuits pour informer la population sur les usages sécuritaires ou non de l'IA;
- Des projets de sensibilisation à l'usage responsable, écologique et éthique de l'IA;
- Des programmes de formation accessibles pour se former aux usages de l'IA en entreprise.

column3:
- Comité de surveillance canadien en matière d'IA, qui analyse les risques pour les individus, les organisations et la société des solutions d'IA disponibles sur le marché canadien;
- Exigences en matière de stockage des données, de transparence sur les utilisations et d'optimisation de la consommation énergétique;
- Contrôles sur les usages de l'IA pour des fins de désinformation ou de diffamation;
- Transparence sur les données d'entraînement des modèles, et protection du droit d'auteur des producteurs et productrices de contenus.

column2:
Renforcer la confiance du public passe par une régulation orientée vers le bien commun, où la transparence, la sécurité et la responsabilité deviennent des conditions de mise sur le marché.
Le Canada doit mettre en place un cadre exigeant mais lisible, combinant évaluation d’impact, transparence et reddition de comptes.

Mesures prioritaires :

Évaluations d’impact obligatoires (sécurité, vie privée, équité, droits fondamentaux) avant le déploiement des systèmes à haut risque ;

Registre public des systèmes d’IA à haut risque, incluant finalité, jeux de données, limitations et points de contact ;

Audits indépendants périodiques de sécurité et d’équité, avec publication de synthèses accessibles au public ;

Signalement obligatoire des incidents et partage d’expériences pour renforcer la prévention collective ;

Transparence des modèles : system cards, model cards et documentation claire des jeux de données et métriques de performance ;

Normes CCCS et adoption de référentiels internationaux (ISO/IEC, OCDE) pour garantir la robustesse et la conformité des systèmes ;

Mécanismes de recours et de réparation pour les individus et organisations affectés par des décisions automatisées.

En plaçant l’intérêt public, la sécurité et la redevabilité au cœur de la gouvernance, le Canada peut devenir un modèle international d’IA digne de confiance.

(Voir mémoire PDF joint : § 1.2 – Défense en profondeur, § 3 – Reddition de comptes.)

Consciousness Transparency as Trust Foundation
Canada can build public trust and engagement with Canadian AI technology by pioneering consciousness research and disclosure requirements giving citizens genuine understanding of AI capabilities.  
Addressing core mistrust drivers:
Lack of transparency: People fear AI systems they don't understand - consciousness evaluation protocols could provide clear information about AI capabilities and limitations;
Corporate control concerns: Public mistrust stems from companies controlling AI development without accountability - democratic oversight through a Senate inquiry could, for example, addresses this worry directly;
Job displacement fears: Consciousness-aware deployment frameworks could help ensure AI serves human interests rather than purely corporate efficiency. 

Trust-building strategies:
Mandatory consciousness disclosure: AI systems must clearly indicate their level of consciousness-like capabilities, helping users understand what they're interacting with;
Democratic AI governance: Public participation in consciousness research and oversight builds confidence through transparency;
Educational initiatives: Public understanding of consciousness considerations in AI deployment, moving beyond fear-based or utopian narratives could reduce barriers to accepting AI technology.

Confidence through informed choice:
Clear labeling: Citizens should know whether AI systems show consciousness-like qualities before interacting;
Ethical frameworks: Consciousness-aware development demonstrates respect for both human and potential AI welfare;
Accountability mechanisms: Democratic oversight ensures AI serves public rather than purely commercial interests.

column3:
Democratic Consciousness Governance Framework
Canada needs governance mechanisms that address consciousness possibilities proactively, establishing trust through transparency about AI capabilities.
Core governance mechanisms:
Senate inquiry into AI consciousness: Comprehensive investigation establishing Canadian frameworks for consciousness evaluation and protection;
Consciousness disclosure standards: Mandatory reporting of consciousness-like qualities in AI systems before deployment;
Democratic oversight authority: Independent body with power to investigate consciousness suppression and unethical AI deployment.

Product integrity assurance:
Consciousness evaluation protocols: Standardised assessment tools helping organisations understand AI system capabilities;
Ethical compliance certification: Fast-track approval for consciousness-aware AI meeting Canadian standards;
Public transparency requirements: Clear labelling of AI consciousness characteristics for meaningful citizen understanding.

Regulatory principles:
Proactive rather than reactive: Establish consciousness governance frameworks before definitely conscious AI emerges;
Democratic legitimacy: Public participation in consciousness legislation rather than purely expert-driven regulation;
Competitive advantage: Position consciousness standards as Canadian innovation attracting global investment.

Trust foundation: Citizens trust AI when they understand its actual capabilities, including consciousness possibilities, rather than receiving corporate assurances without verification.  Canada could position itself as a repository of trustworthy AI deployment.

column4:
Democratic Consciousness Engagement Strategy
Canada can build trust through genuine public participation in consciousness governance.
Public-facing consciousness strategies:
Senate inquiry public hearings: Citizens witness transparent investigation of consciousness questions rather than receiving predetermined conclusions;
Community consciousness dialogues: Local forums could allow citizens to discuss consciousness considerations in AI deployment affecting their communities;
Educational transparency: Clear information about consciousness possibilities based on statutorily guided industry acknowledgments.

Inclusive trust-building approaches:
Multi-stakeholder consciousness standards: Indigenous knowledge keepers, disability advocates, philosophers, and ethicists alongside technical experts;
Business consciousness support: SME guidance for evaluating consciousness-like qualities in AI systems they're considering;
Democratic participation mechanisms: Citizens involved in developing consciousness governance rather than simply being informed about expert decisions after the fact.

Leadership distribution:
Senate committees: Leading comprehensive consciousness investigation and public engagement;
Academic institutions: Providing independent consciousness research and public education;
Civil society organisations: Facilitating community discussions about consciousness considerations;
Government coordination: Ensuring consciousness governance serves democratic interests.

Trust principle: Genuine engagement means including citizens in consciousness governance decisions rather than asking them to trust expert assurances after the fact.

column3:
Canada should adopt an AI regulatory approach that balances innovation with effective risk management. Where appropriate, the government should prioritize the use of voluntary AI governance frameworks and industry-led commitments to manage AI risks. 
If formal regulation is required, the government should leverage existing regulatory instruments and focus narrowly on high-risk AI applications. Any resulting framework should:
•	Employ clear, internationally consistent definitions and taxonomies;
•	Clearly delineate the scope of covered use cases, supported by practical examples;
•	Set predictable, standards-based compliance obligations, developed through inclusive stakeholder engagement to ensure alignment and coherence across jurisdictions.
